SIMPLE: immovable
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Immovable
<hw>Im*mov"a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Incapable of being moved; firmly fixed; fast; -- used of material
things; <as>as, an <ex>immovable</ex> foundation</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Immovable</qex>, infixed, and frozen round.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Steadfast; fixed; unalterable; unchangeable; -- used
of the mind or will; <as>as, an <ex>immovable</ex> purpose, or a man who
remains <ex>immovable</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Not capable of being affected or moved in feeling or
by sympathy; unimpressible; impassive.</def>
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Law.)</fld> <def>Not liable to be removed;
permanent in place or tenure; fixed; <as>as, an <ex>immovable</ex>
estate</as>. See <er>Immovable</er>, <pos>n.</pos></def>
<rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Immovable apparatus</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>an
appliance, like the plaster of paris bandage, which keeps fractured
parts firmly in place.</cd> -- <col><b>Immovable feasts</b></col>
<fld>(Eccl.)</fld>, <cd>feasts which occur on a certain day of the year
and do not depend on the date of Easter; as, Christmas, the Epiphany,
etc.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Immovable</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Immovable
<hw>Im*mov"a*ble</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which can not
be moved.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <fld>(Civil Law)</fld> <def>Lands and
things adherent thereto by nature, as trees; by the hand of man, as
buildings and their accessories; by their destination, as seeds, plants,
manure, etc.; or by the objects to which they are applied, as
servitudes.</def> <rj><au>Ayliffe.</au> <au>Bouvier.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Immovableness</ent>⟦br⟧
